Self-Correcting Models for Model-Based Reinforcement Learning

(Erik Talvitie: AAAI 2017 )

Link: 
https://openreview.net/forum?id=BkZEuTeOZr

Summary:
  • Motivation
    • When an agent cannot represent a perfectly accurate model of its environment's dynamics, model-based reinforcement learning (MBRL) can fail catastrophically. Planning involves composing the predictions of the model; when flawed predictions are composed, even minor errors can compound and render the model useless for planning.
  • Contribution
    • "Hallucinated Replay" trains the model to "correct' itself when it produces errors, substantially improving MBRL with flawed models. 
    • Main contribution of this paper is that it theoretically analyzes this approach of "Hallucinated Replay", illuminates settings in which it is likely to be effective or ineffective, and presents a novel error bound, showing that a model's ability to self-correct is more tightly related to MBRL performance than one-step prediction error.
  • Technical Details

Combining Model-Based and Model-Free Updates for Trajectory-Centric Reinforcement Learning

(Sergey Levine: PMLR 2017 )

Link: 
http://proceedings.mlr.press/v70/chebotar17a/chebotar17a.pdf

Summary:
  • Instead of using DNN as policy approximator, this paper uses TVLG ("Time-Varying-Linear- Gaussian") Controllers as policy representation, which can process fast optimization with model-based LQR-FLM ("Linear-Quadratic-Regulators-Fitted-Local-Models") and model-free PI^2 ("Policy-Improvement-with-Path-Integrals") algorithms, using sample-based updates.
  • This is a hybrid algorithm based on the two components (LQR-FLM and PI^2) where the PI^2 update is performed on the residuals between the true sample-based cost and the cost estimated under the local linear models.
  • Procedure for optimizing time-varying linear gaussian (TVLG) policies that integrates both fast model-based updates via iterative linear-Gaussian model fitting and corrective model-free updates via the PI^2 framework.

Temporal Difference Models: Model-Free Deep RL for Model-Based Control

(Sergey Levine: ICLR 2018)

Link: 
https://arxiv.org/pdf/1802.09081.pdf

Summary:
  • TDM ("Temporal Difference Models") learns "variable-horizon-goal-conditioned-value-functions" which with shorter horizons it corresponds to a "model" and with longer horizons it corresponds to "model-free" approach. 
    • "Goal-conditioned-value-functions" learn to predict the value function for every possible goal state. That is, they answer the following question: what is the expected reward for reaching a particular state, given that the agent is attempting (to optimally as possible) to reach it? The particular choice of reward function determines what such a method actually does, but rewards based on distances to a goal hint at a connection to model-based learning: if we can predict how easy it is to reach any state from any current state, we must have some kind of understanding of the underlying "physics."  
  • This connection between model-based and model-free RL can be used to smoothly transition from learning models to learning policies, obtaining rich supervision from every sample to quickly gain a moderate level of proficiency, while still converging to an unbiased solution. 
  • Important point is while other hybrid methods focus on combining different model-based and model-free RL techniques, this method proposes an "equivalence" between those two branches of RL through a special generalization of goal-conditioned value function.

Model-Based Priors for Model-Free Reinforcement Learning

(Sergey Levine, et al.: CoRL 2017 : Retracted paper due to identification of similar work in the past after submission)


Link: 
https://arxiv.org/abs/1709.03153

Summary:
  • Bridges the gap between Model-Free and Model-based RL by first learning a probabilistic dynamics model then leveraging it as a prior for the interleaved model-free optimization. 
  • This approach learns a dynamics model from scratch which is used to compute the trajectory distribution corresponding to a given policy, which in turn can be used to estimate the cost of the policy. This estimate is used by a Bayesian Optimization-based Model-Free policy search to guide the policy optimization. 
  • This approach uses the Model-Based return estimates as a bias for Model-Free policy learning, but the Model-Based component is incorporated as a prior mean into a Bayesian model-free update, which allows this approach to reason about the confidence of the Model-Free estimates across the entire policy space.
  • This approach learns the dynamics model of the system, and uses Bayesian Optimization (which uses Gaussian Process as underlying objective function) to find optimal policy parameters.
  • Gaussian Process provides both the expected value of the function at any arbitrary point as well as a notion of uncertainty of this estimate.
    • This paper uses Gaussian Process within Bayesian Optimization to map policy parameters to predicted cost. Also Gaussian Process is used to learn the unknown dynamics model.
    • Central to the choice of Gaussian Process is its capability of explicitly modeling the uncertainty in the underlying function. This uncertainty allows to account for the model-bias in the dynamics model, and to deal with the exploration/exploitation trade-off in a principled manner in Bayesian Optimization.

Model-Based Value Expansion for Model-Free Reinforcement Learning

(Sergey Levine, et al.: arxiv 2018)


Link: 
https://arxiv.org/abs/1803.00101v1

Summary:
  • This paper proposes a "model-based value expansion" which controls for uncertainty in the model by only allowing imagination (virtual data generation) to a fixed depth.
  • This paper proposes a method that tries to reduce sample complexity while supporting complex non-linear dynamics by combining Model-Based and Model-Free learning techniques through disciplined model-use for value estimation.
    • Model is incorporated into the "Q-value target estimation", making the model only required to make forward predictions.
  • MVE (Model-Based Value Expansion) improves value estimates for a policy by assuming we have an approximate dynamical model ( f^{hat} ) and the true reward function ( R ).
    • Such an improved value estimate can be used in training a critic for faster task-mastery in reward-dense environments.

Model-based learning retrospectively updates model-free values

(Max Doody, et al.: nature 2022)


Link: 
Model-based learning retrospectively updates model-free values (nature.com)

Summary:
  • Hybrid of Model-based and Model-Free based on insight from neuro-science.
  • "Two-stage decision task" is utilized. In this task, participants make two sequential decisions to obtain a reward.
  • Two concepts are traditionally used to think about "model-based behavior" in "two stage decision task"
  • [Concept-1]
  • "model-based learning", which refers to 2 processes.
  • (process-1)
  • the learning of transitions and the structure of the task through state prediction errors ('state-learning'), 
  • (process-2)
  • subsequently, learning the value of the states at stage 2 ('state value learning')  
  • These processes consequently result in the production and refinement of an internal model of the task structure.
  • [Concept-2]
  • "model-based decision making", refers to how participants make choices utilizing the model.
  • Traditional approach is:                       "Forward Planning" which model-based individuals use their internal model to 'prospectively' assess which path is more likely, to lead to the stage-2 state with highest state-value.
  • However, this paper proposes:
  • <Following is Key Ideas of paper>
  • At the 'time of reward', subjects could 'retrospectively update' the action value of the stage-1 choice depending on whether they received a common or rare transition trial. On the next trial, at the 'time of decision', the most valuable action would then be selected.
  • In this approach, reward is propagated back through the causal chain to the action that is most likely to lead to a reward, taking into account the transition probabilities.
  • At the core of such a process would be a type of model-based RPE ('reward prediction error') that is used to update the value not of the chosen action, but rather of the action that most likely would have led to the current state.
  • In the simplest case, this would generate a prediction error at the time of outcome relative to the model-free value of the action that 'commonly' leads to the actual stage-2 state. In other words, "Backward-Planning" could be used to update the stage-1 model-free values when reward is received"
  • "model-based update": reflecting whether the state encountered was likely or unlikely to follow the option that was selected.

Neural Network Dynamics for Model-Based Deep Reinforcement Learning with Model-Free Fine-Tuning

(Sergey Levine, et al.: ICRA 2018)


Link: 
https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/8463189

Summary:
  • This approach uses the model-based algorithm to initialize a model-free learner. The learned model-based controller (which uses MPC for its own training) provides good rollouts, which enable supervised initialization of a policy ("imitation policy") that can then be fine-tuned with model-free algorithms (such as policy-gradients).
  • This paper demonstrates effective model-based reinforcement learning with neural-network models. Note that it was difficult to combine model-based algorithms with high-capacity and expressive deep neural networks.
